doc.ContractDescription: ACCRETING BLACK-HOLE SYSTEMS SUCH AS X-RAY BINARIES (XRBS) AND ACTIVE GALACTIC NUCLEI (AGN) EXHIBIT PERIODICITIES ON TIME SCALES RANGING FROM MILLISECONDS TO TENS OF DAYS. THE MECHANISM DRIVING THIS VARIABILITY AND THE RELATIONSHIP BETWEEN SHORT- AND LONGTERM VARIABILITY IS POORLY UNDERSTOOD. ADDITIONALLY, HOW THE CHANGES IN BLACK-HOLE MASS, ACCRETION RATE, AND ENVIRONMENT AFFECT THE VARIABILITY ON SCALES RANGING FROM STELLAR-MASS BLACK HOLES TO SUPERMASSIVE BLACK HOLES IS ONLY RECENTLY BEING STUDIED. WE ARE NOW AT A STAGE IN WHICH NASA SPACE TELESCOPES HAVE BEEN TAKING DATA FOR OVER A DECADE, PROVIDING MANY CYCLES TO OBSERVE THE BREADTH OF VARIABILITY. COMPUTATIONAL RESOURCES HAVE ALSO EXPANDED DRAMATICALLY SUCH THAT THE ROLE OF RADIATION AND HOW IT COUPLES TO THE DYNAMICS OF THE ACCRETION DISK CAN NOW BE STUDIED. WE PROPOSE TAKING FULL ADVANTAGE OF THE DATA PROVIDED BY HEASARC TO CREATE MULTI-DECADE LIGHT CURVES COMBINED FROM MULTIPLE MISSIONS TO PERFORM TIME SERIES ANALYSES ON BLACK-HOLE SYSTEMS. THIS ANALYSIS WILL THEN ILLUMINATE A COMPUTATIONAL INVESTIGATION INTO HOW PHYSICAL MECHANISMS, SUCH AS THE INFLUENCE OF RADIATION, MIGHT CHANGE FROM STELLAR-MASS BLACK-HOLES TO AGN. OUR GOAL IS TO INFORM THE EXPECTED BEHAVIOR OF SUCH SYSTEMS FOR FUTURE TIME-DOMAIN MISSIONS SUCH AS WFIRST AND LSST.

UNIQUE THERMAL AND ENVIRONMENTAL BARRIER COATINGS (T/EBCS) COMPOSED OF DOPED RARE EARTH SILICATES WILL BE INVESTIGATED, INCLUDING THE KINETICS OF THE THERMOCHEMICAL REACTIONS WITH CMAS MATERIALS, AS WELL AS THE THERMAL AND MECHANICAL PROPERTIES OF EBC-CMAS SYSTEMS, SUCH AS THE COEFFICIENT OF THERMAL EXPANSION, HARDNESS, FRACTURE TOUGHNESS, AND ELASTIC MODULUS. DIFFERENTIAL SCANNING CALORIMETRY (DSC) MEASUREMENTS WILL BE OBTAINED AT DIFFERENT HEATING RATES AND SEVERAL ISOCONVERSIONAL METHODS ARE USED TO DETERMINE THE ACTIVATION ENERGY AND OTHER KINETIC PARAMETERS OF CRYSTALLIZATION, IN ORDER TO OBSERVE THE STABILITY OF EBC-CMAS COMPOSITIONS. COATINGS OF ENHANCED COMPOSITIONS WILL BE DEPOSITED VIA ELECTRON BEAM-PHYSICAL VAPOR DEPOSITION (EB-PVD), AIR PLASMA SPRAY (APS) AND PLASMA SPRAY-PHYSICAL VAPOR DEPOSITION (PS-PVD). VARIOUS EBC-CMAS SYSTEMS WILL BE EVALUATED FOR TEMPERATURE STABILITY, WATER VAPOR STABILITY, EROSION RESISTANCE, AND CMAS MITIGATION USING SCANNING ELECTRON MICROSCOPY (SEM) AND X-RAY DIFFRACTION (XRD). WHEN COMPARED TO CURRENT TECHNOLOGY EBCS, THESE COATINGS WILL EXHIBIT IMPROVED CMAS RESISTANCE AND PHASE STABILITY AT ELEVATED TEMPERATURES. THESE UNIQUE TBCS AND EBCS WILL ALLOW FOR INCREASED OPERATING TEMPERATURES, AND THUS INCREASED EFFICIENCIES FOR GAS TURBINE ENGINES.
